{"sequence":21,"timestamp":"2026-04-13T22:57:53.620202694Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-1-8655d1c3","body":"finding_summary: `run.pid` cleanup is racy after the writer lease is released, so an exiting run can delete a successor run's PID file.\nseverity: high\naffected_files: [\"src/adapters/fs.rs\", \"src/cli/run.rs\", \"src/contexts/automation_runtime/cli_writer_lease.rs\"]\nline_refs: [\"src/adapters/fs.rs:635-647\", \"src/cli/run.rs:3439-3443\", \"src/cli/run.rs:3673-3680\", \"src/cli/run.rs:4055-4061\", \"src/contexts/automation_runtime/cli_writer_lease.rs:130-153\"]\nremediation_hint: Remove `run.pid` while the caller still owns the writer lock, or move PID-file cleanup into the same critical section as lease release; a read-then-`remove_file` on the path is not safe once another owner can acquire the project.\nexplanation: `remove_pid_file_if_matches()` rereads `run.pid` and then unlinks the path. Every caller in this bead does that after `lock_guard.close()` / lease release, so a new start or resume can acquire the writer lock and rewrite `run.pid` between the compare and the unlink. The old process then deletes the successor's PID record, which makes a live run look stale and can trigger incorrect stop/resume recovery against an active orchestrator.","dedup_key":"9de6c13831c0762260b36aa7765e193949bc3d50a8c580e0e8d5c0844f115475","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260413224245","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
